data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions and overload resolution rules. On an `int[]`, `.Contains()` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`** (`IEnumerable<T>`-based). Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so it fails at runtime.

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` so the compiler picks `Enumerable.Contains`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches force the `IEnumerable<T>` overload, which expression trees can represent. This pattern applies to any array `.Contains()`, `.Reverse()`, or similar call inside an expression tree that now resolves to a span extension method.
